======================================================================
WHY IS H=21 PERMANENTLY IMPOSSIBLE?
======================================================================

--- Part 1: β₁+2β₂ → H mapping ---

  n=5:
  Target=10 (β₁+2β₂=10) achievable: NO
    β₁+2β₂= 6: H expected= 13, actual H ∈ [13]
    β₁+2β₂= 7: H expected= 15, actual H ∈ [15]

  Does H = 1+2(β₁+2β₂) always hold? (ignoring β₃+)
    Mismatches: 0 (these have β₃+ > 0)

  n=6:
  Target=10 (β₁+2β₂=10) achievable: NO
    β₁+2β₂= 6: H expected= 13, actual H ∈ [13]
    β₁+2β₂= 7: H expected= 15, actual H ∈ [15]
    β₁+2β₂= 8: H expected= 17, actual H ∈ [17]
    β₁+2β₂= 9: H expected= 19, actual H ∈ [19]
    β₁+2β₂=10: H expected= 21, actual H ∈ [] ← TARGET
    β₁+2β₂=11: H expected= 23, actual H ∈ [23]
    β₁+2β₂=12: H expected= 25, actual H ∈ [25]
    β₁+2β₂=13: H expected= 27, actual H ∈ [27]
    β₁+2β₂=14: H expected= 29, actual H ∈ [29]

  Does H = 1+2(β₁+2β₂) always hold? (ignoring β₃+)
    Mismatches: 0 (these have β₃+ > 0)

--- Part 2: Structural constraint analysis ---
  Q: Why can't we get β₁+2β₂=10 with β₃=β₄=...=0?
  A: This would need β₁+2β₂=10 with no independent triples.
     Let's examine what (β₁,β₂) pairs exist at each n.

  n=5: (β₁, β₂) patterns near target line β₁+2β₂=10:
    ( 7, 0):    64 tournaments, sizes={3: 280, 5: 64}, mults={1: 280, 2: 24, 3: 40}

  n=6: (β₁, β₂) patterns near target line β₁+2β₂=10:
    ( 6, 1):   720 tournaments, sizes={3: 2880, 5: 1440}, mults={1: 4320}
    ( 7, 0):  2208 tournaments, sizes={3: 9120, 5: 5088}, mults={1: 13440, 2: 288, 3: 480}
    ( 8, 0):   720 tournaments, sizes={3: 2880, 5: 2880}, mults={1: 5760}
    ( 9, 0):  1440 tournaments, sizes={3: 7200, 5: 5760}, mults={1: 12960}
    ( 9, 1):  1440 tournaments, sizes={3: 7200, 5: 4320}, mults={1: 10080, 2: 1440}
    (11, 0):  1440 tournaments, sizes={3: 8640, 5: 7200}, mults={1: 15840}
    (11, 1):   480 tournaments, sizes={3: 2400, 5: 1920}, mults={1: 3840, 3: 480}
    (12, 0):  1440 tournaments, sizes={3: 8640, 5: 5760}, mults={1: 11520, 2: 2880}

